import java.util.*;

public int nearestExit(char[][] maze, int[] entrance) {
    int m = maze.length;
    int n = maze[0].length;
    int[][] directions = {{0, 1}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {-1, 0}};
    Queue<int[]> q = new LinkedList<>();
    maze[entrance[0]][entrance[1]] = '+';
    q.offer(new int[]{entrance[0], entrance[1]});
    int steps = 0;

    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        int size = q.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
            int[] cur = q.poll();
            int x = cur[0];
            int y = cur[1];
            if ((x == 0 || x == m - 1 || y == 0 || y == n - 1) && (x != entrance[0] || y != entrance[1]))
                return steps;

            for (int[] dir : directions) {
                int xx = x + dir[0];
                int yy = y + dir[1];
                if (xx >= 0 && xx < m && yy >= 0 && yy < n && maze[xx][yy] == '.') {
                    maze[xx][yy] = '+';
                    q.offer(new int[]{xx, yy});
                }
            }
        }
        ++steps;
    }

    return -1;
}
```


    The algorithm uses Breadth-First Search (BFS) to traverse the maze. It first marks the entrance as a wall ('+'). Then it adds the entrance coordinates to a queue. We also declare a variable to keep track of steps.

While the queue is not empty, we iterate through each level of the BFS tree, processing each cell at a given depth. We check if the current cell is at the border of the maze and not the entrance cell. If so, we return the current number of steps.

If the current cell does not satisfy the exit condition, we explore its adjacent cells. We iterate through each possible direction (up, down, left, and right) and calculate the next cell's coordinates. If the next cell is inside the maze and not a wall, we mark the next cell as a wall ('+') and add it to the queue. After processing all cells at the current depth, we increment the steps.

If the BFS is completed and there is no valid exit, return -1.
